article.description:
Sam Cassell scored 24 points and Tim Thomas
added 21 as the Milwaukee Bucks beat the Detroit Pistons 109-86
Saturday night in the second game of a back-to-back set between the
teams.
article.headline: Cassell, Thomas help Bucks avenge earlier loss
article.linkText: Cassell, Bucks return to .500 with win vs. Pistons
article.story:
MILWAUKEE (AP) -- One night after losing to the Pistons, the Bucks got some revenge.
Cassell

Sam Cassell scored 24 points and Tim Thomas added 21 Saturday night as Milwaukee bounced back from a loss and defeated Detroit 109-86. Michael Redd added 20 points for the Bucks, while Richard Hamilton led Detroit with 15 points and Cliff Robinson added 14. "I think we scared Detroit a little last night (in the 96-91 Pistons' win),'' said Milwaukee coach George Karl, whose team evened its record at 8-8. "We had good activity tonight, good concentration. We rebounded well (40-39 edge). I think we can be a good rebounding team if everybody goes to the glass like tonight.'' Detroit coach Rick Carlisle said his team, despite a 12-5 record, seemed to have lost a "mental edge on defense'' that it had earlier in the season. "They just beat us in every area of the game,'' Carlisle said. "Their effort was great and ours was sub-par. That combination produced a blowout. They played a great game and we weren't up to it.'' Thomas scored 10 points in the third quarter to help the Bucks increase a 10-point halftime lead to 87-68 by the end of the period. Milwaukee led by as many as 28 points in the final quarter. The Bucks shot 57 percent (44 of 77) for the game. "We had a good game,'' said Cassell, who added 10 assists. "We defended well. We made the shots we should have.'' The Bucks established an offensive flow early in the game, shooting 75 percent (15 of 20) and outrebounding the Pistons 12-5 for a 33-24 lead at the end of the first quarter. Detroit cut the margin to six points, 53-47, in the second quarter, but the Bucks built the lead back to 62-52 by halftime. Cassell had 17 points in the first half and got the Bucks into their open court game. "Sam played great,'' Hamilton said. "He led his team. He was running things out there tonight. They came out hot early and just kept going from there. They had a great shooting night." Game notes
Bucks rookie F Marcus Haislip is day-to-day with a sprained right ankle. G Ray Allen was walking on his sprained right ankle without pain and could be ready to come off the injured list by next Thursday. ... Detroit's Zeljko Rebraca did not play in the second half because of back problems. ... Pistons guard Chauncey Billups remains day-to-day with a sprained right ankle. ... The Pistons had beaten the Bucks three straight times.
